    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1926989">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1926989">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1926989)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1926989">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1388698406 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Jan 2014 21:33</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1926989">
									

<p>So, I have a certain level of tolerance for coming into the middle of the narrative and finding out more information as the story moves along. Which is what was happening in the original tale, which I liked.</p>
<p>Thing is, at some point, you need to give me <em>something</em> as a reader to keep me hooked and to make me feel like I at least am privy to some sort of information as to what the hell is going on here. In the first tale, there were things that we didn't know, chiefly what it is that the protagonist did that got him demoted, beaten up, and assigned to what is apparently a sort of penal unit. I was on board with that. The disciplinary proceedings and reactions of the people involved were somewhat understandable in that context.</p>
<p>Now, I don't expect you to fill in all the blanks immediately after the action resumes. But I also feel like maybe you could have given me, the reader, a little more to go on before dumping like eighteen more mysterious things in my lap. I mean, we have:</p>
<ul>
<li>Amnestics aren't working like they should anymore, for some mysterious reason</li>
<li>The workings of the group the protagonist is assigned to, which I don't really get at all. Is he the leader now? The crazy guy seems to be in charge at times, but not really.</li>
<li>Whatever it is the lady they're showing up to take out (although their intent as what they're going to do with her is also kind of unclear) is doing, and what it is that she saw</li>
<li>The two people in the truck, which make absolutely no discernible sense to me (I get the impression that this something of the &quot;a reality bender did it so it doesn't have to make any sense&quot; persuasion)</li>
<li>Whatever it is that's speaking at the end</li>
</ul>
<p>On top of all that, we are still no closer to what it is the protagonist did, or what its significance (if any) is in relation to the continuing action.</p>
<p>I feel like I could have gone along with one or two additional unknown things being introduced into the larger story, but all together I'm mostly just befuddled. You've tried to balance that, it looks like, by giving us a little more of the characters that make up the crew, but it's not really interesting enough to me to offset my confusion as to what the hell is going on here.</p>

							</div>

								
					
