					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dmatix" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1366080); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1366080&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204947" alt="Dmatix" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1366080)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dmatix" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1366080); return false;" >Dmatix</a></span> <span class="odate time_1388698810 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Jan 2014 21:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1926996">
									

<p>I understand this, and I think I can of at least one reason to your confusion. This tale wasn't originally supposed to end at the point that it did. It became a two-parter simply because it was getting too long and unwieldy to be posted in one piece. The last three points you raised are all addressed in the second part (which was supposed to be the end of this tale). I realize that this is a small comfort, but it should be addressed nonetheless.</p>
<p>As to the first two points, since those are some of the overarching plot points of the entire series, I felt that covering them entirely in the first two tales would be somewhat premature. I realize this has its downsides, however.</p>
<p>Regardless, thanks for taking your time and commenting. This is all very useful information.</p>
<p>E: Oh, and I should probably point out that the couple in the car have appeared before in Djoric's <a href="/three-sleepless-nights">Three Sleepless Nights</a>. I suspect that reading that tale would also serve to dispel some of the confusion.</p>

							</div>

								
