    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1927009">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1927009">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1927009)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1927009">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1388699525 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Jan 2014 21:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1927009">
									

<p>We've touched on this a little in chat before, and I understand the limitations that expected length places on serialization here. I don't view it as an insurmountable problem, but I do get that it makes things more difficult to execute. Wanting to avoid the risk of making this article's discussion page a symposium on tales, I'll leave it at that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>E: Oh, and I should probably point out that the couple in the car have appeared before in Djoric's Three Sleepless Nights. I suspect that reading that tale would also serve to dispel some of the confusion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That would indeed provide some background info here. However, I'll share a personal preference of mine for references of existing works here. I feel that in a standalone piece, as this overall story of yours is, outside references to works that are not widely accepted by large swathes of human culture shouldn't be relied upon to carry a story. I view these kinds of references as ways to deepen the experience of the knowledgeable reader, not as built-in heuristics for moving a story forward. As such, I would have liked to have seen a little more set up for this part so that someone reading this story wouldn't be required to read some other piece in order to understand events crucial to the action.</p>

							</div>

								
					
