					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/nighkos" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1658000); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1658000&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204947" alt="Nighkos" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1658000)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/nighkos" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1658000); return false;" >Nighkos</a></span> <span class="odate time_1388703561 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Jan 2014 22:59</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1927071">
									

<p>Since you specifically asked for people who read the first tale to comment: I have to say, this one didn't really do it for me. The first one was very cerebral and character driven, whereas this one is far too dialogue heavy. It was a bit of a disappointment since diving into the psychopath's mind was what I really liked about the first. Seeing how this crazy, messed up person views this crazy, messed up world. Seeing the perspective of a guy, who in some ways, has more in common with the skips than his fellow Foundation personnel.</p>
<p>I also agree a lot with what Kalinin mentioned. Most prominently, in my opinion, is that the EWU cameo is lasts a bit to long. That length leads to covering a lot of points, which in turn leads to some confusion. I think I would have liked it a bit better if it was a bit more subtle - a quick nod rather than a long discussion.</p>

							</div>

								
					
